<paragraph id="8BC336E9D20E9D233AD4D9A5ED0DFF42" blockId="27.[136,893,157,185]" box="[136,893,157,185]" pageId="27" pageNumber="162">
<heading id="D08B8185D20E9D233AD4D9A5ED0DFF42" box="[136,893,157,185]" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="27" pageNumber="162" reason="3">
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D6AD20E9D233AD4D9A5ED76FF43" authority="R. H. Thompson (1950: 296)" authorityName="R. H. Thompson" authorityPageNumber="296" authorityYear="1950" box="[136,774,157,185]" class="Dinophyceae" family="Peridiniaceae" genus="Sphaerodinium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Peridiniales" pageId="27" pageNumber="162" phylum="Myzozoa" rank="species" species="fimbriatum">
<emphasis id="B908EAFBD20E9D233AD4D9A5EFB5FF42" bold="true" box="[136,453,157,184]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="162">Sphaerodinium fimbriatum</emphasis>
R.H.Thompson (1950: 296)
</taxonomicName>
. 
<figureCitation id="13472A6CD20E9D23394DD9A6ED0DFF42" box="[785,893,158,184]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="27.[136,229,1991,2013]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,965,1967]" captionTargetId="figure-320@27.[164,1423,965,1967]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 18. Sphaerodinium fimbriatum. A Ventral view. B Dorsal view. C SEM ventral view. D. Epithecal plates. E. Hypothecal plates. Bar= 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5426123" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5426123/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="162">Figure 18</figureCitation>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC336E9D20E9D233AD4D9DEEC15FEFA" blockId="27.[136,1452,230,940]" box="[136,613,230,257]" pageId="27" pageNumber="162">Dimensions: L: 43–45 µm, Td: 34–39 µm.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3666562D20E9D233AE1D832EDB8FC56" pageId="27" pageNumber="162" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BC336E9D20E9D233AE1D832EC06FE96" blockId="27.[136,1452,230,940]" pageId="27" pageNumber="162">
Cell shape: Rounded, oval, dorsoventrally slightly compressed. Plate margins very prominent as fimbriate lists, present in both the epithecal and the hypothecal plates (
<figureCitation id="13472A6CD20E9D2338A1D816ED15FEB2" box="[765,869,302,328]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="27.[136,229,1991,2013]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,965,1967]" captionTargetId="figure-320@27.[164,1423,965,1967]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 18. Sphaerodinium fimbriatum. A Ventral view. B Dorsal view. C SEM ventral view. D. Epithecal plates. E. Hypothecal plates. Bar= 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5426123" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5426123/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="162">Fig. 18C</figureCitation>
). Prominent plate margins, both in the epitheca and the hypotheca, in the form of fimbriate lists.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC336E9D20E9D233AE1D84EEF7EFE06" blockId="27.[136,1452,230,940]" pageId="27" pageNumber="162">
Thecal characteristics: Tabulation, 4ʹ, 4a, 7ʹʹ, 7c, 6s, 6ʹʹʹ, 2ʹʹʹʹ (
<figureCitation id="13472A6CD20E9D2339CED84EEA06FE6A" box="[914,1142,374,400]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="27.[136,229,1991,2013]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,965,1967]" captionTargetId="figure-320@27.[164,1423,965,1967]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 18. Sphaerodinium fimbriatum. A Ventral view. B Dorsal view. C SEM ventral view. D. Epithecal plates. E. Hypothecal plates. Bar= 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5426123" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5426123/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="162">Figs. 18C and 18D</figureCitation>
), without apical pore. The plate 1ʹ narrow, elongated, flanked by 2ʹ and 4ʹ plates, and not contacting 1ʹʹ and 7ʹʹ plates (
<figureCitation id="13472A6CD20E9D233EC9D8A2EA86FE4E" box="[1173,1270,410,436]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="27.[136,229,1991,2013]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,965,1967]" captionTargetId="figure-320@27.[164,1423,965,1967]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 18. Sphaerodinium fimbriatum. A Ventral view. B Dorsal view. C SEM ventral view. D. Epithecal plates. E. Hypothecal plates. Bar= 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5426123" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5426123/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="162">Fig 18C</figureCitation>
). This character does not appear in the order 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D6AD20E9D233B93D886EC27FE22" baseAuthorityName="Haeckel" baseAuthorityYear="1894" box="[463,599,446,472]" class="Dinophyceae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Peridiniales" pageId="27" pageNumber="162" phylum="Myzozoa" rank="order">Peridiniales</taxonomicName>
. The 3ʹ is hexagonal and the four anterior intercalary plates are almost isodiametrical.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC336E9D20E9D233AE1DB3EEC89FDBE" blockId="27.[136,1452,230,940]" pageId="27" pageNumber="162">
Cingulum and sulcus: Equatorial cingulum. Narrow sulcus, the Sa plate enters into the epitheca and is in contact with the first and the last pre-cingular plates (
<figureCitation id="13472A6CD20E9D2338D9DB12EC9CFDBE" box="[645,748,554,580]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="27.[136,229,1991,2013]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,965,1967]" captionTargetId="figure-320@27.[164,1423,965,1967]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 18. Sphaerodinium fimbriatum. A Ventral view. B Dorsal view. C SEM ventral view. D. Epithecal plates. E. Hypothecal plates. Bar= 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5426123" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5426123/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="162">Fig. 18C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC336E9D20E9D233AE1DB76ECE7FD2E" blockId="27.[136,1452,230,940]" pageId="27" pageNumber="162">
Ornamentation: The margins of the plates, very prominent, easily visible with light microscopy (
<figureCitation id="13472A6CD20E9D233F58DB76EB1BFD92" box="[1284,1387,590,616]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="27.[136,229,1991,2013]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,965,1967]" captionTargetId="figure-320@27.[164,1423,965,1967]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 18. Sphaerodinium fimbriatum. A Ventral view. B Dorsal view. C SEM ventral view. D. Epithecal plates. E. Hypothecal plates. Bar= 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5426123" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5426123/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="162">Fig. 18B</figureCitation>
). The margin border present outstanding nodules, such as fimbriae (
<figureCitation id="13472A6CD20E9D233911DB4AEDC5FD76" box="[845,949,626,652]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="27.[136,229,1991,2013]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,965,1967]" captionTargetId="figure-320@27.[164,1423,965,1967]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 18. Sphaerodinium fimbriatum. A Ventral view. B Dorsal view. C SEM ventral view. D. Epithecal plates. E. Hypothecal plates. Bar= 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5426123" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5426123/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="162">Fig. 18C</figureCitation>
). The epithecal plates have a rough texture, without any ornamentation, while each hypothecal plate has a central prominent strip, similar in appearance to the projections of the plate margins (
<figureCitation id="13472A6CD20E9D233BA5DB82ECFAFD2E" box="[505,650,698,724]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="27.[136,229,1991,2013]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,965,1967]" captionTargetId="figure-320@27.[164,1423,965,1967]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 18. Sphaerodinium fimbriatum. A Ventral view. B Dorsal view. C SEM ventral view. D. Epithecal plates. E. Hypothecal plates. Bar= 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5426123" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5426123/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="162">Figs. 18C, E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC336E9D20E9D233AE1DBE6ED75FD02" blockId="27.[136,1452,230,940]" box="[189,773,734,760]" pageId="27" pageNumber="162">
Localities: Ayapel and Zapatosa in North 
<collectingCountry id="F36B7679D20E9D2338D3DBE6ED71FD02" box="[655,769,734,760]" name="Colombia" pageId="27" pageNumber="162">Colombia</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC336E9D20E9D233AE1DA3AEC8EFC72" blockId="27.[136,1452,230,940]" pageId="27" pageNumber="162">
Commentaries: This is the first record of both the genus and the species 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D6AD20E9D2339B9DA3AEB62FCE6" authorityName="R. H. Thompson" authorityYear="1950" box="[997,1298,770,796]" class="Dinophyceae" family="Peridiniaceae" genus="Sphaerodinium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Peridiniales" pageId="27" pageNumber="162" phylum="Myzozoa" rank="species" species="fimbriatum">
<emphasis id="B908EAFBD20E9D2339B9DA3AEB62FCE6" box="[997,1298,770,796]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="162">Sphaerodinium fimbriatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry id="F36B7679D20E9D233F6ADA3AEBD8FCE6" box="[1334,1448,770,796]" name="Colombia" pageId="27" pageNumber="162">Colombia</collectingCountry>
. The species is an easily recognizable, due to the shape of the theca and the curved edges when observed with LM. The specimens observed match the original description (
<bibRefCitation id="EFED4B18D20E9D23388FDA72EDFDFC9F" author="Thompson, R. H." box="[723,909,842,869]" pageId="27" pageNumber="162" pagination="277 - 299" refId="ref16610" refString="Thompson, R. H. (1951) A new genus and new records of fresh-water Pyrrophyta in the Desmokontae and Dinophyceae. Lloydia 13: 277 - 299." type="journal article" year="1951">Thompson 1951</bibRefCitation>
) and are in the size range (
<tableCitation id="C6FE0352D20E9D233E9CDA72EB55FC9E" box="[1216,1317,842,868]" captionStart="TABLE 10" captionStartId="28.[136,224,159,183]" captionText="TABLE 10. Variation of length (L) and trans-diameter (Td) of Sphaerodinium fimbriatum in Colombia. (n=10 in each locality)." pageId="27" pageNumber="162">Table 10</tableCitation>
) mentioned in the literature (
<bibRefCitation id="EFED4B18D20E9D233B1EDA56EFB5FC72" author="Carty, S." box="[322,453,878,904]" pageId="27" pageNumber="162" refId="ref14134" refString="Carty, S. (2014) Freshwater Dinoflagellates of North America. Cornell University Press, New York, 272 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.7591 / 9780801470370" type="book" year="2014">Carty 2014</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFED4B18D20E9D233B93DA56EC82FC72" author="Moestrup, O. &amp; Calado, A. J." box="[463,754,878,904]" pageId="27" pageNumber="162" refId="ref16007" refString="Moestrup, O. &amp; Calado, A. J. (2018) Susswasserflora von Mitteleuropa. 6. Dinophyceae. B. Budel, G. Gartner, L. Krienitz &amp; M. Schagerl (Eds.) Springer, Berlin, 561 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / 978 - 3 - 662 - 56269 - 7 _ 7" type="book" year="2018">Moestrup &amp; Calado 2018</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
